<!-- ══════════ FAQ ══════════ -->
<section class="section" id="faq">
  <div class="container faq-wrap">
    <span class="overline">FAQ</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">Everything travelers ask before visiting Little Boracay in Calatagan, Batangas.</p>
    <div class="faq-accordion">
      <details class="faq-item" open>
        <summary>What is Little Boracay in Calatagan, Batangas?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>Little Boracay is a <strong>natural tidal sandbar</strong> off the western coast of Calatagan, Batangas, Philippines. Known for its shallow turquoise waters, white sand, and iconic floating bamboo cottages. It is not a beach resort — it is a natural destination accessed by boat from the coastal barangays of Calatagan.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How far is Little Boracay from Manila?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>Calatagan, Batangas is approximately <strong>3 to 4 hours from Metro Manila</strong> by car, depending on traffic. The route uses the South Luzon Expressway (SLEX) and STAR Tollway heading south.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How do I book a floating cottage at Little Boracay?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>Use the <a href="#book">Plan Your Visit form</a> on this page, visit our <a href="/contact">Contact page</a>, or message us on <a href="https://facebook.com/littleboracay" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Facebook</a>. We recommend booking at least 2–3 days ahead on weekends and Philippine holidays.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Is Little Boracay the same as Boracay Island in Aklan?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>No. Little Boracay is a <strong>completely separate destination</strong> in Calatagan, Batangas. It earned the nickname because of similar white sand and turquoise water. Boracay Island is in Malay, Aklan and requires a flight and ferry from Manila.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is the best time to visit Little Boracay?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>Morning to early afternoon during low tide is ideal. The <strong>dry season (November to May)</strong> offers the most reliable weather and calmest seas. Avoid typhoon season (June–October) when possible, or check with us first.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Is Little Boracay family-friendly?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. The <strong>shallow, calm waters</strong> make it perfect for families including young children. The entire sandbar area is suitable for non-swimmers and waders. Adult supervision is always recommended.</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What should I bring to Little Boracay?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>Essentials: <strong>cash (PHP)</strong> — most operators don't accept cards; high-SPF sunscreen; swimwear; waterproof sandals; dry bag for phone and valuables; drinking water; packed meals or snacks. Optional: snorkeling gear, waterproof camera, drone (check CAAP rules).</p></div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How far is Little Boracay from CaSoBe or Stilts Resort?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>Both CaSoBe (Calatagan South Beach) and Stilts Beach Resort are located nearby along the Calatagan coastline. Many visitors combine these stops in a single day trip to Calatagan, Batangas.</p></div>
      </details>
    </div>
    <div style="margin-top:24px;text-align:center;">
